    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about an escrow account for the closing and i'm kinda confused. what exactly is escrow and why do i need it for the house purchase?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "An escrow account is basically a neutral, third-party vault where your money and the seller's funds are held safely until the closing date, ensuring neither party can steal or misappropriate the funds. You need it because it acts like a strict, impartial referee in the transaction, making sure all the legal paperwork is signed, the title is clear, and the funds are transferred correctly before the keys are handed over. Without this escrow process, you'd be risking your hard-earned cash sitting in someone else's pocket without any guarantee that the house is actually yours by then.\n\nThink of it like a very organized, slightly nervous group of tiny goblins who are constantly shuffling papers and counting coins in a locked room. While you are busy looking at the kitchen cabinets and the goblins are busy making sure the seller's deed is perfect and your down payment isn't accidentally eaten by a rogue goblin, the escrow officer is just the one in charge of the goblin nest. They hold the money until the goblins confirm that every single condition of the contract has been met, at which point they release the funds to the buyer and seller simultaneously.\n\nIt's a bit like a high-stakes game of musical chairs where the chairs are",
      "source": "target",
